This modern park offers a little bit of everything for everyone. The park is devided by a railway but connected through elevated walkways, so don‚Äôt forget to check out the other side. It‚Äôs big enough for runners. There‚Äôs a skatepark for skaters, plenty of lawns for picnicking, and a playground for kids. That‚Äôs why quite crowded on the weekends. Dogs are not allowed in the park though.
Fantastic park and green space. Lots of water fountains, with Paris water clean and safe to drink. Many people having picnics and enjoying the weather.

This park is a nice little haven in the middle of all the urban development. There is a lot of construction going in the surrounding area and the park provides a very welcome break from that. There is modern landscaping all around with ample of place to sit or play for both adults and kids respectively. There are also washroom facilities located within the park itself which helps if once decides to stay for a longer time. It can get a little crowded on weekends.

A very quiet and beautiful park with lots of vegetation. The modern buildings near the park are also a sight. There's a skateboard park, some chairs to sit on and a small place where children can play.

A good place to enjoy your time. Lush green environment. Seperate areas for kids under age 3 and older kids. Jogging track. Benches available to sit and read a book or chat with your friend. Enjoy hot smoke bath. Open arena for skatters. A family park in 75017 Paris.

Very nice skatepark although I would not recommend bring  young children for their safety. If you do bring children there is a fun looking outdoor play structure with slides and pretend ‚Äúkitchen space and things like that‚Äù
Large green area. Small water-body inside. There is dedicated place for kids and young people to skate and bike. One can jog, walk or just take a sit to enjoy the green!

A beautiful place with a lot of things and space to do. It has a big playground for kids but also a dedicated skateboard üõπ trick place and not to mention a closed tennis ground place for adults.  Compatible for every age and close by a metro and a bud station. More than anything it is beautiful to walk in abig enough to picnic too. It gives a relaxing feeling of a resort retreat and a modern design. üòå Definitely worth visiting. And a tiny water area with a cute mother goos with her offspring. üòç

This park and the park beside it should be the textbook example of brilliant cityscaping. u have public transport, higher occupancy apartment (mix of low and high cost), and a huge park with sports areas and lots of open space with wildlife! There is even a resident heron that the locals recognize.  Good job city of Paris

It's park for all and it was Nice and amazing place. Many trees, many bench for everybody. Park for children wasn't that bad only not many things for 12 months and below. Its more on 1 1/2 year and onwards
Modern park with many new buildings around
Nice park. There are lot of cherry blossoms around March to April.
Great clean park. Be careful: no dogs allowed and it closes at night.
Nice park surrounded by modern buildings. An architectural achievement
Have nice playground for kids, lots of seats around. Good to enjoy little"balade en famille" and picnic.
very nice place for an afternoon walk, great scenery, grass and trees. highly recommend to visit the parc.
Good park, has half pipe and other equipments to play.
Brand new park, for all ages, skate park too. Clean, safe, jogging trails, young families.
A very nice parc situated in a good area and the cherry blossoms have already blossomed in March
Nice for city run early morning but it opens only 7am..
Small and cool place. It has a mini fitness space

Fantastic! Came across this whilst looking for somewhere to play football, and what a gem it is. Skatepark, play areas, squash and basketball courts. Vast amounts of seating and grassed areas. Free water refill machine and an ice cream cart. Highly recommended place to visit.
It's good place to have your training , rest, fun, just peaceful place to be for anything peace ‚úåÔ∏è,i love it there.
Newer urban park with trails and walkways, perfect for strolling, running, watching ducks
Very nice park, very big with a lot of green areas. There is also a small skate park in the middle. It's different from other views in Paris as it is surrounded by new designed cool buildings.
I really like this park. Cool architecture around. There are toilets. Lots of runners. In March/ April the blossoms are really beautiful. Opening times change throughout the year.

The park is very spacious, there is something to enjoy for everyone from play grounds for toddlers, skateboard rinks, basketball court and a wall to practice tennis, a football field. There are a lot of benches and lounge chairs, plenty of space on the ground/grass to sit on. There are ponds that have fishes and migratory ducks and birds. There are toilets and drinking fountains. Mid March is probably the best time to visit, to catch the cherry blossoms in full bloom.
Another beautiful park in Paris, landscaped with imagination. Popular with joggers and parents with children.
Lovely park for walks and sun taking.
Very quiet place in Paris sorrounded by nature and people doing their things... running, having lunch, sunbathing, chating, walking their dogs, reading, or simply watching others, like I did.
Too much people but nice park
Super nice park with cherry flowers
small but delightful park. A picnic mat and book are all I need for a relaxing afternoon here
Nice park with lots of Sakura.
Fantastic modern park!
Fantastic new park. The pinnacle of municipal design. Leslie Knope would be beside herself.

A small space, although there seems to be a lot of development underway. A skate park and some thoughtfully planned seating areas, at different levels,  to provide a range of vistas. Very contemporary architecture, surrounding. Ducks in the water and plenty of joggers, families, kids even on this freezing day. I suggest getting some lunch at the nearby street market and eating it here, watching the local life stream by.
